While the join command has several options, here is a summary of the most commonly used ones:

Basic joining of two files based on a common field
Customizing the output order using the -o option
Including unmatched records with the -a option
Joining on fields other than the first column using the -1 and -2 options

Key join Options
-1 FIELD: Join on the specified field (column) of the first file.
-2 FIELD: Join on the specified field (column) of the second file.
-j FIELD: Equivalent to -1 FIELD -2 FIELD.
-a FILE_NUMBER: Print unpairable lines from the specified file (where FILE_NUMBER is either 1 or 2).
-o FORMAT: Obey the specified format for the output (e.g., 1.1 2.2 to show the first column of the first file and the second column of the second file).
-t CHAR: Use CHAR as the input and output field separator instead of whitespace.
-i: Ignore case differences when comparing fields.
-e STRING: Replace missing input fields with the specified STRING.
-v FILE_NUMBER: Similar to -a, but suppresses the lines that were successfully joined (only shows the unmatched ones).
